  "prompt": "Can the statement \"X is n times less or smaller than Y be justified when n>1?",
  "response": "The statement \"X is n times less or smaller than Y\" can be problematic and potentially misleading, especially when \\( n > 1 \\). The phrase can lead to confusion because it is not mathematically precise and can be interpreted in various ways.\n\nTo clarify, let's consider what \"n times less\" might imply. Suppose \\( n = 2 \\):\n\n**Interpretation 1:**\nIf \"X is 2 times less than Y,\" it might be interpreted as:\n\\[ X = Y - 2Y = -Y \\]\nThis is clearly not the intended meaning since it implies a negative value, which is not typically the way we discuss proportions in this context.\n\n**Interpretation 2:**\nAnother interpretation could be:\n\\[ X = Y / 2 \\]\nThis is often the meaning that people intend when they say \"2 times less.\" That is, \\( X \\) is half of \\( Y \\).\n\nFor larger values of \\( n \\):\n\nSuppose \\( n = 3 \\):\n**Common Interpretation:**\nIf \"X is 3 times less than Y,\" it is commonly intended to mean:\n\\[ X = Y / 3 \\]\n\nHowever, this phrasing is still ambiguous and not mathematically rigorous. The better way to state this is:\n\"X is one-third of Y\" or \"X is \\( \\frac{Y}{n} \\).\" This is direct and clear without room for misinterpretation.\n\n### Formal Example\nGiven \\( Y = 100 \\):\n- \"X is 3 times less than Y\" (interpreted as \\( Y / 3 \\)):\n  \\[ X = 100 / 3 \\approx 33.33 \\]\n\n### Conclusion\nFor clarity and precision, it is preferable to avoid the phrase \"n times less\" and instead use formulations such as:\n- \"X is one-nth of Y.\"\n- \"X is \\( \\frac{Y}{n} \\).\"\n\nThese formulations are mathematically precise and leave no ambiguity regarding the relationship between \\( X \\) and \\( Y \\).",
